ch 5 summary:
1. Context & Purpose of Replication
 Definition: Keeping a copy of the same data on multiple machines connected via a
network.
 3 Core Benefits:
1. Lower Latency: Keeps data geographically close to users.
2. High Availability: System continues working even if some nodes fail.
3. High Read Throughput: Scales out the number of machines serving read
queries.
 Assumption: Each machine holds a copy of the entire dataset.
2. Single-Leader Replication (Master-Slave / Active-Passive)
 Mechanics: * Leader (Master/Primary): Only node that accepts writes. Writes are
recorded locally first.
o Followers (Slaves/Secondaries/Read Replicas): Read-only nodes. They
consume the leader's replication log or change stream and apply writes in the
exact same order.
o Reads: Clients can read from the leader or any follower.
Synchronous vs. Asynchronous Replication:
 Synchronous: Leader waits for the follower's confirmation before reporting success to
the client.
o Pro: Follower is guaranteed to have up-to-date data.
o Con: If the follower crashes, all writes on the leader are blocked.
 Semi-Synchronous: One follower is synchronous, and the others are asynchronous. If
the synchronous node fails, an asynchronous one is promoted.
 Asynchronous: Leader sends the update but doesn't wait for a response.
o Pro: Leader can process writes continuously even if all followers fall behind.
o Con: Un-replicated writes are lost if the leader fails completely.
Setting Up New Followers (Zero-Downtime Workflow):
1. Take a consistent snapshot of the leader's database without locking it.
2. Copy the snapshot to the new follower node.
3. Follower requests all data changes since the snapshot using an exact position track (Log
Sequence Number in Postgres, Binlog Coordinates in MySQL).
4. Follower processes the backlog until it has caught up.
Handling Node Outages:
 Follower Failure: Easy recovery via Catch-up recovery. Follower reads its local log to
identify the last transaction before the crash, then requests the missing stream from the
leader.
 Leader Failure (Failover Workflow):
1. Detection: Nodes bounce messages; if a node doesn't respond within a timeout
(e.g., 30s), it is declared dead.
2. Promotion: A follower (usually the one with the most up-to-date data) is chosen
via an election or appointed by a controller node.
3. Reconfiguration: Clients are rerouted to the new leader.
 ـ Failover (Critical Exam Pitfalls):
o Discarding un-replicated writes violates client durability expectations.
o Split Brain: Two nodes both believe they are the leader simultaneously. If both
accept writes, data becomes corrupted.
o Short timeouts cause unnecessary failovers during temporary load spikes,
worsening the problem.
Implementation of Replication Logs:
1. Statement-based Replication: Leader logs and sends every SQL statement (INSERT,
UPDATE).
o Breakdown Risk: Fails if statements call nondeterministic functions (NOW(),
RAND()), use autoincrementing columns, or trigger side effects.
2. Write-Ahead Log (WAL) Shipping: Append-only physical byte stream describing
exact disk blocks changed.
o Disadvantage: Closely coupled to the storage engine format. Prevents running
mismatched database versions between leader and follower, making zero-
downtime upgrades impossible.
3. Logical (Row-based) Log Replication: Decoupled from storage engine internals;
outputs data at the granularity of a row. Allows backward compatibility and easy parsing
by external systems (Change Data Capture).
4. Trigger-based Replication: Moves replication to the application layer via database
triggers. High overhead and bug-prone, but highly flexible for custom subset replication
or conflict handling.
3. Problems with Replication Lag & Consistency Models
 Read-Scaling Architecture: Creating many asynchronous followers to serve read-heavy
web traffic.
 Eventual Consistency: Followers will eventually catch up, but during high load or
network glitches, the replication lag can cause temporary read inconsistencies across
different replicas.
Core Replication Anomalies & Guarantees:
1. Reading Your Own Writes (Read-after-write consistency):
o The Problem: A user submits data (sent to leader) but immediately reloads the
page and reads from a stale follower, making their entry look lost.
o The Guarantee: Ensures a user always sees updates submitted by themselves.
o Solution: Read the user's own editable profile strictly from the leader; track the
timestamp of the last update and force leader reads for 1 minute post-write.
2. Monotonic Reads:
o The Problem: A user makes successive reads from different replicas. They read
from a fresh follower first, then refresh and read from a lagging follower. Time
appears to go backward.
o The Guarantee: Ensures a user will not read older data after having previously
read newer data.
o Solution: Ensure a user always queries the same replica (e.g., routing based on a
hash of the User ID).
3. Consistent Prefix Reads (Causality Violation):
o The Problem: In partitioned databases, if an answer is replicated faster than the
question, an observer sees the effect before the cause.
o The Guarantee: Ensures that if a sequence of writes happens in a certain order,
anyone reading them sees them appear in that same order.
o Solution: Any causally related writes must be routed to the same partition.
4. Multi-Leader Replication (Master-Master / Active-Active)
 Concept: Allows more than one node to accept writes. Each leader simultaneously acts
as a follower to other leaders.
 Use Cases: Multi-datacenter operations (hides network latency across the internet,
tolerates datacenter outages), offline client operation (every device has its own local
leader database), and real-time collaborative editing (e.g., Google Docs).
Handling Write Conflicts:
 Single-leader databases block or abort concurrent writes. Multi-leader setups accept both
writes successfully, and the conflict is only detected asynchronously later.
 Conflict Avoidance: The recommended approach. Route all writes for a specific record
to a single designated "home" datacenter so conflicts cannot occur.
 Convergent Conflict Resolution (Achieving Consistency):
o Last Write Wins (LWW): Throws away older writes based on a timestamp.
High risk of silent data loss.
o Replica ID Precedence: Higher-numbered replica ID wins. Also causes data loss.
o Merge Values: Concatenates or merges conflicting records alphabetically.
o Custom Logic: Triggering application code handlers on write (background
process) or on read (returns multiple versions called siblings to the user).
 Automatic Conflict Resolution Families: CRDTs (Conflict-free replicated datatypes),
Mergeable persistent data structures (Git-like 3-way merges), and Operational
Transformation (collaborative text editing logic).
Multi-Leader Topologies:
 Circular Topology: Each node forwards writes in a ring.
 Star/Tree Topology: A designated root node forwards writes.
o Flaw for Circular & Star: If a single node fails, it breaks the entire replication
chain.
 All-to-All Topology: Every leader communicates with every other leader. Better fault
tolerance but prone to writes overtaking each other due to network speeds, violating
causal ordering.
5. Leaderless Replication (Dynamo-Style)
 Concept: Abandoning the concept of a leader; any replica can directly accept writes
from clients. Used in Riak, Cassandra, and Voldemort.
Mechanics of Node Outages:
 Writing: Client sends the write to all $n$ replicas in parallel. If a node is down, the write
is considered successful as long as a minimum number of nodes ($w$) acknowledge it.
 Reading: Client queries multiple nodes in parallel. It uses version numbers to identify
and discard stale values returned by recovered nodes.
Data Recovery Mechanisms:
1. Read Repair: When a client reads from multiple nodes and spots a stale value, it
immediately writes the newest version back to that stale replica. (Only works for
frequently read data).
2. Anti-Entropy Process: A continuous background process that looks for data differences
between replicas and copies missing data. Unordered and can have significant delays.
Quorum Conditions (n, w, r):
 n = Number of replicas.
 w= Minimum votes required for a write to be successful.
 r = Minimum nodes queried for a read operation.
 Strict Quorum Condition: w + r > n* This condition guarantees that the write set and
read set must overlap by at least one node, ensuring the client reads the most up-to-date
value.
o If w + r \le n, the quorum condition is violated, and the system is highly likely to
read stale values.
Limitations of Quorums (Why stale values still occur):
 Sloppy quorums move writes away from home nodes, breaking the guaranteed overlap.
 Concurrent writes can be dropped or lost due to clock skew during LWW resolution.
 If a write succeeds on fewer than $w$ replicas, it is not rolled back, meaning subsequent
reads might still see it.
Sloppy Quorums and Hinted Handoff:
 Sloppy Quorum: If a network link cuts off a client from its home nodes, the database
accepts writes anyway on alternative, reachable nodes outside the designated $n$ home
set.
 Hinted Handoff: Once the network fault is resolved, the temporary nodes
asynchronously transfer the writes back to their original home nodes.
 Trade-off: Increases write availability, but breaks strict quorum read guarantees until the
handoff finishes.
Detecting Concurrent Writes
 Concurrency Definition: Two operations are concurrent if they are unaware of each
other (no causal dependency or happens-before relationship). Exact physical time does
not matter.
 Capturing Causal Dependencies:
o Server maintains and increments a version number for every key on each write.
o Client must read the key first to get the current value and version number.
o When writing, the client must pass that version number back and merge all
siblings (concurrent values).
o Server overwrites values with that version number or lower, but keeps higher
version numbers as conflicts.
o Tombstone: A deletion marker written to indicate an item was removed,
preventing it from reappearing when merging siblings.
 Version Vectors: Used in leaderless distributed environments. A collection of version
numbers is maintained per replica, per key to distinguish overwrites from concurrent
updates across multiple nodes